Wash and dry all produce.

Trim and thinly slice @Persian Cucumber{1} crosswise on a diagonal.

In a #large bowl{}, combine @shredded red cabbage{4%oz}, @shredded carrots{4%oz}, and @sesame dressing{1.5%oz}. Taste and season with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and a pinch of @sugar{} if desired.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{4%tbsp} with @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%oz} to taste.

Pat @diced steak{10%oz} dry with #paper towels{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over high heat. Add steak and cook until browned and cooked to desired doneness, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @sweet soy glaze{4%tbsp} and cook until steak is coated, ~{1-2%minutes} more. Turn off heat.

While steak cooks, halve and toast @demi-baguette{2} in a #toaster{}.

Divide cucumber slices between bottom halves of baguettes. Top with saucy steak and a bit of sesame slaw (save the rest for serving). Pick and tear @cilantro{1/4%oz} leaves from stems; sprinkle leaves over slaw. Spread chili mayo on cut sides of top buns and close sandwiches.

Divide banh mi between plates. Serve with remaining sesame slaw on the side.

> It's okay if the sandwiches are a bit messy—just bring some extra napkins to the table!